body:
Yes, the C example isn't clear for multiple outputs as it was just a simple example with a single output.

The second to last parameter of OrtRun is the # of outputs you expect it to return (and also the size of the OrtValue* array you're passing as the last parameter. If you want two outputs you need to pass an array of two pointers, and pass a 2 for the output_names_len parameter.

So yes, it's a pointer to an array of pointers as you suggested above.

The C++ example makes it more clear in that the return value from Session::Run is plural but only contains a single element:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/9e926fef1cf7c0ed9ccde5e88453fd91266f3c9b/csharp/test/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.EndToEndTests.Capi/CXX_Api_Sample.cpp#L111

Did that help to get it to work?
